manualautomixed (recommended) <p>All columns use <code>default_width</code>, except those with an explicit <code>width</code>.</p> <pre><code>{"width_mode": "manual", "default_width": 15.0}
</code></pre> <p>Calculates width based on the largest content in each column.</p> <pre><code>{"width_mode": "auto", "auto_padding": 2.0}
</code></pre> <p>Uses explicit <code>width</code> when defined; otherwise, calculates it automatically.</p> <pre><code>{
    "width_mode": "mixed",
    "columns": {"ID": {"width": 8.0}}  # fixed ID, rest auto
}
</code></pre>

Option Type Default Description <code>chunk_size</code> <code>int</code> <code>200</code> Number of rows per chunk. Lower = less RAM, higher = less overhead. <code>paragraph_threshold</code> <code>int</code> <code>30</code> Character limit to use <code>Paragraph</code> with automatic line breaks. <pre><code>spec = ReportSpec(
    output_format="pdf",
    columns=[...],
    metadata={
        "pdf": {
            "chunk_size": 100,  # less memory per chunk
        }
    },
)
</code></pre> <p>Memory Model</p> <p>PDF uses chunked streaming — each block of <code>chunk_size</code> rows is rendered and  discarded before processing the next one. Peak memory is O(chunk_size × n_columns),  not O(n). Still, PDF is ~200x slower than CSV/XLSX. For datasets over 50K rows, prefer CSV or XLSX.</p>
